Beijing's natural ecology continues to attract more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle" in the city
2020-07-26 05: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Siyu Responsible Editor: Wang Siyu
The natural ecology of the capital continues to improve to attract wildlife cities to "settle"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
(Reporter Wang Bin) The reporter of Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Bureau of Landscape and Greening that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the natural ecological environment in the capital, the species and quantity of wild animals have continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wildlife living in Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national protected animals such as zebra, swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Both the urban forests planted everywhere in the Second Ring and the small micro-wetlands embedded between the buildings have not only brought the wildlife to the citizens of the capital, but also attracted wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the middle of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is vibrant.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by a mountain stream, while two badgers were playing with each other.
In retrospect, a wild boar couldn't help its "scratching" and was rubbing hard against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Administration, said that as of the end of 2019, there were 178 kinds of wild animals, including gold carvings of state-protected animals and state-protected animals of the second class, including chicken and gazelle, living in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares. Nearly one-third of the wildlife species in the city can be seen here.
"In Matsuyama, wild animals are the real 'masters'. At best, our staff can only be regarded as the 'bodyguards' of others."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the wildlife in the protected area on the ground, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and make a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day almost all over the protected area.
"During the inspection, we should not only check and record the biodiversity, but also check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras and so on."
Songshan National Nature Reserve has installed more than 200 infrared cameras to record the living conditions of wildlife in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli said that with the continuous enrichment of the biodiversity of the protected areas in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera. Leopard cats, raccoons and badgers have become "permanent guests," and the "visibility rate" of the state's second-level protected animal, the gazelle, has become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, Director of Wildlife and Wetland Protection of Beijing Landscape and Greening Bureau, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wildlife in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 species today, and the variety and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
Wild animals are becoming more and more common in cities, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of urban greening in the capital in recent years.
In particular, the new round of million-acre afforestation construction, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland green space and highlight the concept of "near nature."
The plan strives to connect and interact with the surrounding green areas to make it easier for wild animals to "visit relatives and friends," and the trees planted are also favorite honey and food plants for animals.
