The FAA urgently ordered the investigation of 2,000 Boeing airliners - Xinhua News
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valve of the above-mentioned airliners may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) said that it has received four reports of engine air parking of 737NG and 737Classic airliners so far, so it has made an urgent inspection request. The inspection targets are airliners that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more and airliners that have flown less than 11 times since they were put back into flight.
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if the Class 5 check valves of both engines of the airliner were corroded, they might jam in the open position, causing the airliner to lose power completely and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, air operators must replace this key component before the airliner is put into use again.
Boeing responded later that day that the outbreak of the new crown caused travel demand to decrease, so many airliners were sealed or used less, "check valves are more susceptible to corrosion."
At the same time, Boeing said it has advised air operators to inspect the airliners involved in the instructions. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
According to the Associated Press, airliners owned by major US airline operators usually fly many times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown disease, a large number of airliners stopped flying; with the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some airliners have returned to operation.
The Federal Aviation Administration did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners was on its way from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas, on July 15, when one of its engines suddenly stopped, and the airliner finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engines of the airliner and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with the instructions of the Federal Aviation Administration.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that their airliners had no engine failure related to the air check valve.
Four airliners of American Airlines will be inspected and 28 airliners of United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine failure.
According to many media reports, the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
One Boeing 737MAX of Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
The series of airliners were subsequently suspended worldwide, shut down in January this year and resumed production in May.
The head of the Federal Aviation Administration, Steve Dickson, admitted in June that the Federal Aviation Administration had "made a mistake" in regulating Boeing with regard to the 737MAX.
