Ko Xili Tibetan antelope enters the migration season - Xinhua
Xining, Xinhua News Agency, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Ko Xili Management Office of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that the monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelope that had migrated to the Chunai Lake area in the hinterland of Ko Xili to give birth to their babies were gradually ending giving birth and returning to their original habitat with their babies.
Monitoring pictures near the Wudaoliang Protection Station show that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelope led three young Tibetan antelope to cross the 3002 km of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelope has begun to move back.
Experts analyzed that in recent years, the number of young Tibetan antelope in the returning sheep accounted for one quarter to one fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope.
Lien Xinming, associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "At the beginning of the migration, the Tibetan antelope faced a higher risk of being preyed on. Therefore, the number of young in the sheep would be relatively small, and there might even be no young."
According to the statistics of Ko Xili Management Office of Changjiangyuan Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the overall number of Tibetan antelope relocations is increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelope relocations was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lien Xinming said, "It is expected that the return migration of Tibetan antelope will end in early September this year. The number of returning Tibetan antelope is still expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelope is a national level protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelope from the source of the Three Rivers in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet and Alshan in Xinjiang go to Zhuonai Lake, located in the hinterland of Koxili, to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on the protection of Tibetan antelope in China and a researcher at the Institute of Zoology of Shaanxi Province (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said, "The return migration of Tibetan antelope is the process by which the female Tibetan antelope returns to her habitat with her young after the end of childbirth. At first, the return migration group that leaves the nursery is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelope will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of the Tibetan antelope herd, the reporter learned that the Ko Xili Management Office of the Changjiang Yuan Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration had arranged staff to carry out continuous video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation areas.
If a herd of Tibetan antelope is found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the sheep to pass through the wildlife passage safely to ensure that they are not disturbed by humans on the way back.
So, how to relieve the heat in daily life?
Experts suggest that it is best not to walk or work in the hot sun around noon when going out in summer, because the sun is the strongest in this time and the possibility of heatstroke is higher.
If you have to go out at this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as taking a sunshade, wearing a sunshade hat and wearing sunglasses. It is best to apply sunscreen if you have conditions to prevent sunburn.
Try to choose light-colored cotton, hemp and silk with good air permeability, and wear less chemical fiber clothing to avoid not dissipating heat in time when sweating in large quantities, causing heatstroke.
In hot and sultry weather, you should prepare enough water to drink and drink it in time. Don't wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, the body is short of water. Control drinking water to 150 ml to 200 ml at a time. Drink warm boiled water, not ice water.
According to the temperature, the average staff drink 1.5 to 2 liters of water per day, while the high-temperature workers drink 3 to 5 liters of water per day.
When sweating more, you can appropriately supplement some salt water to make up for the loss of salt caused by sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to lack of potassium in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired. Tea containing potassium is an excellent summer drink.
In summer, eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumbers and tomatoes; fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons and melons, have a water content of 80% to 90%, which can be used to replenish water; dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high temperature environment should properly supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
The days and nights in summer are long, the temperature is high, the metabolism of the human body is exuberant, the consumption is also large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax the brain and body systems, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heatstroke.
Experts say that the best bedtime is from 22: 00 to 23: 00 and the best wake-up time is from 5: 30 to 6: 30.
Be careful not to lie under the air conditioner outlet and electric fan during sleep in order to avoid air conditioning disease and hot cold.
Experts suggest that people engaged in outdoor activities or high-temperature work can carry with them heat-proof drugs such as ten drops of water, mandarin, patchouli gas or patchouli gas pills, or place them in a nearby workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
