Graduate Art Exhibition Moved into Shopping Mall for Public Interest Exhibition - Xinhua
In the "cloud graduation" season of major colleges and universities, a rare offline graduate art exhibition opened warmly last weekend.
However, it is not in the art gallery or campus, but in the public space of Grand Hyatt City in Chaoyang. It is open to the public free of charge and will last until August 23.
The reporter learned that the 2020 graduate art exhibition collected 50 pieces / groups of works by 57 young artists from the Central Academy of Fine Arts, Communication University of China and Tianjin Academy of Fine Arts. The exhibition space was extended from the second floor to the sixth floor, and the light box in the building was used to display flat works to maximize the artistic atmosphere of the graduation season.
Under the epidemic, the significance of this exhibition is particularly special.
"We choose to bring the graduation exhibition to the" cloud "back to the offline space. We also hope to let more people see young people's exploration of themselves and understanding of the world, and to amplify the healing power of art to society and the heart," said Ge Ping, head of Chen Mei, Dayue City, Chaoyang.
She revealed that the works participating in the exhibition were collected from the graduates of several major art colleges, from which the works suitable for commercial space were selected, ranging from traditional shelf paintings and sculptures to new media installations, interactive animation and VR panoramas, with the largest volume and richness in the past year.
Among them, Li Yunshao expressed his feelings in the epidemic through a mix of mechanical and manual creative language in "The First Battle of 2020"; Liu Jiaying's work "Sound Money" through Ethereum blockchain explored the themes of "cryptocurrencies," "credit creation," "transactions," and so on; Zhang Jiaqi's "Cat Forest" and Qiu Darqiang's "Bohemian" both show animals that often accompany human beings, from which young artists can see their understanding of the relationship between human beings and animals; while Zhu Zhongyu's work "Winter of Faith - Gift" is a reminder to young people growing up that "when one day you have a successful career, don't forget your first heart, remember that simplicity and sincerity."
Among the few graduates who exhibited in person was Li Jingyin from the Department of Sculpture of Tianjin Academy of Fine Arts.
"I came to Beijing on July 7. I was actually a little worried about the epidemic. I also had a nucleic acid test three days in advance. I came to the exhibition with alcohol cotton and the test report."
His work Yesterday Is a Mystery has a complex structure and must be done by himself.
