Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) member trade ministers held a video conference on July 25, at which they pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Leaders' Informal Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting said that the trade ministers of APEC members recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time.
All parties pledged to ensure that the emergency measures taken in response to the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent, and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, and comply with World Trade Organization rules.
In the statement, the trade ministers of APEC members pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by enhancing the flexibility of supply chains, and minimize the disruption to the flow of medical supplies, food, and agricultural products in order to cope with the epidemic.
The trade ministers of APEC members agreed that it is necessary to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict the trade of necessary goods, and reaffirmed their commitment to promote the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The conference also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration stated that economies would ensure that their trade measures in response to the epidemic were in line with WTO provisions, and pledged to take actions in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to facilitate the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
Azmin Ali, Minister of International Trade and Industry of Malaysia, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting and the work of formulating the vision of APEC cooperation beyond 2020 is advancing in an orderly manner.
