French Defense Minister Florence Parly said on the 24th that France will increase its space defense budget by hundreds of millions of euros to develop military forces in space in order to prevent other countries from possible "unfriendly actions" in outer space.
Palley told Le Provence on the same day that between 2019 and 2025, the French space military project expenditure budget will increase from 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion US dollars) to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion US dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to upgrade its existing observation satellites and communications satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and improve the modernization of space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a military space command and an "aviation and space force" would be established within the French Air Force.
Palley said she would officially announce the establishment of the space force when she visited a military school in Salon, Provence.
Palley said that the space force belongs to the Air Force and will have 500 personnel by 2025.
She said: "The idea that space served the common interests of science is gone forever. Nowadays, space is the place where countries compete for global hegemony."
Palley reiterated Macron's previous statement that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my duty to fully understand the threats we may face."
Palley recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that the "voyeur" was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denied this claim.
Palley said that France will soon have a small patrol satellite capable of detecting and locking "those behind unfriendly actions."
French media believe that France sought to establish a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill to establish the Pacific Air Force last February.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act last December, approving the establishment of the Pacific Air Force, the sixth type of U.S. military.
Some experts worry that these US measures accelerate the pace of US space militarization and may trigger a new space arms race.
