Economic Watch reporter Rao Xianjun On July 26, Greenfield Holdings (600606.SH) issued the "Indicative Notice on the Proposed Transfer and Relicensing of Some Shares of the Company by State-owned Shareholders through Public Collection of Transferees."
According to the announcement, in order to further deepen the reform of state-owned enterprises, optimize the structural adjustment of the layout of state-owned enterprises and improve the ownership structure of green space, Shanghai Real Estate (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as "Shanghai Real Estate") and Shanghai CIC (Group) Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as "Shanghai CIC") intend to transfer some of the company's shares by agreement through public solicitation of transferees, and the total proportion of shares to be transferred shall not exceed 17.5% of the total share capital of green space.
The price of the shares to be transferred is not lower than the higher of the following: the arithmetic average of the daily weighted average price for the 30 trading days before the indicative announcement day (July 27, 2020); and the audited net asset value per share of the company in the most recent fiscal year.
At present, there is still uncertainty about the new strategic investors of Greenfield. According to the public announcement, it is estimated that the new strategic investors will need to pay about 14 billion yuan to acquire the 17.5% equity transferred in the mixed reform of Greenfield.
It is worth noting that after the completion of the share transfer, Greenfield is still expected to have no controlling shareholders or actual controllers, but the control structure may change considerably.
Since its establishment, Greenfield Holdings has carried out a number of institutional reforms: from 1992 to 1997, it operated under the purely state-owned system in accordance with market-oriented rules; from 1997 to 2013, it established and continuously improved the joint-stock system of state-owned holdings and employee shareholding; from 2013 to 2015, it introduced strategic investors to form a mixed ownership system of cross-shareholding and integration of state-owned and non-public capital; from 2015 to date, it has been listed as a whole and has become a public company.
Greenfield's current mixed reform plan is similar to that of Gree. In December 2019, Zhuhai Mingjun, the leader of high-level capital, took over the 15% stake of Gree Electric Appliance (000651.SZ) for 41.662 billion yuan. Gree Group retired as a minority shareholder. After completing the mixed reform, Gree Electric implemented modern enterprise management methods such as executive incentive plan and unreal controller structure.
Shanghai Real Estate and Shanghai City Investment are state-owned enterprise groups wholly owned by the Shanghai State Administration Commission. Zhang Yuliang, chairman and president of Greenfield Holdings, said that Greenfield's move is an important measure for Shanghai to promote the comprehensive reform of state-owned state-owned enterprises and accelerate the reform of state-owned state-owned enterprises in the new stage in accordance with the requirements of the Party Central Committee. It fully demonstrates the new reform ideas adapted to local conditions and tailored to local conditions, and supports enterprises to further improve the degree of marketization, enhance the freedom of operation and management, and accelerate the full release of the reform vitality by introducing new excellent strategic shareholders to listed companies.
