Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old to sue the university after being smashed in the playground?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Siyu Responsible Editor: Wang Siyu
When the playground was smashed, the child got compensation and then sued the school.
- Zhao Yifan, correspondent of this newspaper
While playing in the playground of a university, 3-year-old Xiao Wen was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while throwing a ball.
After Chen made compensation, Xiao Wen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiao Wen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, requesting the school where the playground was located to make an apology and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and moral damages.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had fulfilled its obligation of proper safety and security by setting up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and that Chen had paid compensation. According to the judgment, the plaintiff's claim was rejected.
Mr. Wen complained that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play in the school playground while the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents moved in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, Chen Mou, a member of the softball team, broke off while throwing the ball, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiao Wen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believed that the facilities of the school stadium did not meet the relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The negligence of the school led to the above-mentioned incident, which caused Xiao Wen to suffer great physical and mental pain, as well as great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, posted management regulations and training notices, told the school to keep a safe distance from the training venue and reminded itself of its own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school had "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations" and therefore did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the venue of the incident was a venue open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school had safety and security obligations for the management of the playground, such safety and security obligations only needed to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, which had fulfilled the obligation of proper safety and security, and Chen also compensated Xiao Wen more than 2,000 yuan for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses in accordance with the compensation agreement previously reached. The two sides agreed to settle the dispute once.
Later, Xiao Wen's parents again claimed the school compensation, which was unfounded in the law, and the court decided to reject all the plaintiff's claims.
After the judgment, neither party appealed and the judgment has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation of safety and security; if the actions of a third party cause damage to others, the third party shall bear the liability of infringement, while the managers of public places who fail to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that because the manager of a public place is the most likely to know the actual situation of the whole place, anticipate the possible dangers and damage, and thus the most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the loss or mitigate the extent of the damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the damage is the lowest, the law stipulates that he should bear the corresponding guarantee obligation to engage in social activities.
In this case, for the non-specific entrants in the playground open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of the school should be appropriate to the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should mainly take basic safety measures and be obliged to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on public place managers.
If the school has taken measures to set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal liability.
In addition, for infringement by a third party, even if the administrators of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is also used as a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after assuming the supplementary liability, the administrators can also recover compensation from the third party.
Therefore, in this kind of accident, the victim should not expand the scope of claim after receiving the compensation from the direct infringer.
