Yang Hongnian, founder of Beijing Philharmonic Choir, died at the age of 86.
Beijing News (Reporter Liu Zheng) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir published an obituary. Yang Hongnian, founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor, music educator, lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and professor of the Department of Command, died in Beijing at 13: 55 on July 26, 2020, aged 86, due to ineffective medical treatment.
The picture is from the official website of Beijing Philharmonic Choir.
Born in 1934, Yang Hongnian is a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, and has loved music since childhood.
He was the conductor of the choir of Nanjing People's Radio Station in 1951. In the autumn of 1951, he was admitted to the Department of Music of Shanghai East China Normal University. He studied conducting under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hitzman, and studied style and polyphony with former Soviet expert Alzamanov.
In 1958, he was appointed to teach in the Department of Music of Beijing Art Normal College, and in 1973, he was transferred to teach in the Department of Composing and Command of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
Over the past 30 years, adhering to the tenet of "love and dedication," he has led this choir to sing all over the world and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He conducted the performances of more than 30 groups, including the choir of the Central Orchestra, the Central National Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe and the Shanghai Choir, and held many symphonic and choral concerts.
His books include "Band Training," "Chorus Training," "Two Songs Writing," "Children's Songs Collection" (top and bottom volumes), and his papers "On Choral Phonetics," "On the Sound Layout of Orchestra," as well as his translations of "Choral Accessories" and "Debussy's Harmonic Language."
