China News Service Chongqing, July 26 (reporter Liu Xian) The Chongqing Development and Reform Commission released information on July 26 that the city has retired 4,404 fishermen so far, accounting for 42.54% of all fishermen involved.
Li Daiguo, 53 years old, said in an interview with China News Service that his grandfathers had been fishing in the Longxi River. Since he was 11 years old, he followed his father fishing and rocked his boat along the Longxi River, going up to Liangping, Chongqing, and living a long life. Each time he left home, he spent ten days and a half months fishing to support his family.
However, since 1997, as the rural population gradually poured into the town, there were more and more residents in the town, and the environmental pollution was becoming more and more serious.
Paper mills, chemical factories and fish farms have been built along the Longxi River, which also pollutes the river.
By 2007 and 2008, the Longxi River had become a stink ditch.
"The fish scales caught are all black, and the inside is also black when cut open."
Li Daiguo said it was more and more difficult to fish after the river was polluted.
The local government began to make great efforts to control the pollution of Longxi River, including clear floating, river patrol, and the management and protection of aquatic resources.
Li Daiguo also retired from fishing to production and became a member of the river patrol team to protect aquatic resources.
From January 1, 2020, the Chongqing Aquatic Biological Reserve and the relevant waters of the main urban area have been completely banned from fishing.
According to the data of Chongqing Development and Reform Commission, up to now, Chongqing has a total of 3,403 fishing vessels and 4,643 fishing vessels that have signed withdrawal agreements, accounting for 63.3% and 86.3% of the total tasks for three years, respectively.
There were 4,404 fishermen retired, accounting for 42.54% of all fishermen involved.
Of the 4,404 retired fishermen, 4,267 were employed, accounting for 96.89%.
Old-age insurance covers 2,691 people, accounting for 61.10% of the retired fishermen.
Next, Chongqing will carry out in-depth special remediation actions, accelerate the clean-up and remediation of the utilization project of the Yangtze River dry stream shoreline, complete a new round of survey of sewage outlets into the Yangtze River and carry out corresponding remediation actions, basically complete the remediation task of "tri-phosphorus" (referring to phosphate ore, phosphorus chemical industry and phosphogypsum reservoir), clean up and rectification of small hydropower, promote the special action of afforestation on both sides of the Yangtze River, strengthen the construction of green mines, consolidate the achievements of the special remediation of illegal docks and illegal sand mining in the Yangtze River dry stream, and further promote the prohibition of fishing and fishing in the Yangtze River basin.
Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks - China New Zealand
2020-07-26 04: 56: 44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Siyu Responsible Editor: Wang Siyu
Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
At the beginning of the outbreak of new crown pneumonia, Israel's preventive and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of people diagnosed with new crown pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of new crown pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, which quickly took measures to close all entry and exit ports, suspend non-essential industries, switch schools to online teaching, restrict public transport and non-essential social activities, block cities with severe epidemics, and jointly maintain prevention and control measures.
This series of measures soon achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel fell to single digits.
With the outbreak under control and all prevention and control measures in Israel fully unsealed, the number of newly diagnosed pneumonia has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially in July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the daily number of new cases in Israel has been more than 1,500 for eight days, and as of July 25, the number of new cases on that day had reached 916.
As of July 25, Israel had 59745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
Facing the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gyms, swimming pools, bars and nightclubs, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, stipulating that "city closure" should be implemented from 17: 00 every Friday to 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but places such as shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be prohibited on all dates and time periods, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be prohibited from eating and only take-out services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to form a joint effort with the government to combat it.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's preventive and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, believing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's ban on restaurants, cafes and other preventive and control measures without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the rules of wearing masks and keeping a safe social distance of two meters during outdoor activities. To avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated outbreaks, the school was a major disaster area for the spread of the new crown virus. According to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, it was found that the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the expert advisory panel of Israel's National Security Council to combat the epidemic, believed that Israel was moving towards a "dangerous situation" and pointed out that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the epidemic were not enough. All places of leisure and recreational activities and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic. The parliament and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on combating the epidemic and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions in different sectors.
