The Lancet praises China's anti-epidemic efforts and encourages countries to learn from experience.
According to the article in the 25th issue of Lancet magazine, China, as a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a scale similar to that of Europe or the United States, has effectively controlled the new crown epidemic at this stage, but there has been no widespread spread, and has controlled the domestic epidemic to a large extent.
The article said that in the past ten years, China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction, which makes China much more prepared for the new crown than for the severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
The authors said that when SARS broke out in 2002, China was not well prepared at first, especially the pathogen could not be identified.
When the new crown virus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the virus species and shared the genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had clarified the clinical characteristics of the virus and warned the world of the threat of the new crown virus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research. When the country declared a state of emergency, such research was carried out very quickly and strictly through close cooperation at home. The results of the progress made in the early trials of the new crown vaccine developed by China were published in The Lancet in May and July respectively.
China's experience shows that it is very important to invest in the national health and research system to effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, are well worth learning from.
In addition, China's experience has proved that, on the basis of strong research, strong high-level officials must decisively make correct decisions based on scientific evidence in order to effectively control the new crown epidemic.
The article emphasizes that the government and its leaders must respect science, understand its value, and act on it in the most beneficial way to society.
At the beginning of the outbreak, the National Health and Construction Commission of China sent three groups of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the new crown virus. Their suggestions provided a basis for Wuhan's decision to "seal the city" on January 23. When experts put forward the necessity and urgency of building a square cabin hospital, the government made a decision and implemented it quickly. At the same time, the broad participation of the community and the masses also enabled the epidemic to be controlled quickly and effectively.
Finally, the article emphasizes that countries need to strengthen global cooperation and jointly respond to the global health emergency.
