One winter morning several years ago, in Johannesburg, South Africa, when I drove to work, I found the city shrouded in haze.
I drive there almost every day, but this time is very unusual. I have never seen such a sight before.
Johannesburg is famous for its unique and beautiful skyline, but it could hardly be seen that morning.
Soon I realized that what I saw was the severe haze caused by air pollution.
The contrast between the beautiful environment I used to know and the foggy skyline surged in my heart.
I fear that the once colorful sunset will be swallowed up by the dark haze.
At that moment, I felt a strong impulse to do something, but I didn't know what to do.
All I know is that I cannot just stand by.
The biggest challenge is that I do not understand environmental science, air quality management, or atmospheric chemistry.
I am a computer engineer, and I am quite sure that I cannot solve the problem of air pollution by coding.
(Laughter) In what capacity will I solve this problem?
I am just a small citizen.
In the next few years, I learned a very important lesson that we should all bear in mind if we want to realize a better future.
Even if you are not an expert in a particular field, your professional skills may contain solutions to problems in that field.
Sometimes, your unique perspective can stimulate unconventional thinking and influence the situation, but you need to be bold to try.
Only then can you know the result.
What I knew then was that if I wanted to try to change, I had to know enough about pollution, so I became a student again.
I did some basic research and soon learned that air pollution is the biggest environmental health risk in the world.
According to the World Health Organization, in 2012, almost 14% of deaths worldwide were caused by air pollution in and around homes, especially in low- and middle-income countries.
The annual death rate caused by air pollution is higher than that caused by malaria and AIDS.
In Africa, premature deaths caused by unsafe sanitation, or deaths caused by child malnutrition, are powerless in the face of air pollution, and it also carries huge economic costs: according to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, spending exceeded $400 billion in 2013.
In my work, I explore the scientific and technological frontier achievements of artificial intelligence, including the symbiotic relationship between human beings and machines, to find a useful foothold and help us make better decisions.
When I think of the problem of air pollution again, it becomes clear how to control it. We need to find better ways to make better decisions. Considering the magnitude of the problem, cooperation is very necessary.
So I decided to meet some people working in this field.
I began to talk with officials in Johannesburg and other surrounding cities. I also joined the local science community. I also made some phone calls to completely strangers but related people.
These experiences that I began to intervene helped me to understand the problem more deeply.
It also helped me avoid the trap that people in my profession sometimes fall into when trying to innovate: to adopt a technology quickly before they really master the problem.
I began to think, what can I do to improve the situation?
I began to ask myself how to effectively integrate my knowledge and skills in software engineering and artificial intelligence and the professional skills of the people I contacted.
I want to create an online air quality management platform to reveal future pollution trends and make relevant forecasts to judge the possible results.
I am sure my idea can become a realistic solution, but in the face of uncertainty, I cannot guarantee its success.
All I have is a specific set of engineer skills, skills gained from my work. (Laughter) Of course, for people who have been working in the field of air pollution for many years, my skills are completely new.
I have come to realize that sometimes a novel perspective, a new skill set, can lead to something outstanding.
Our willpower and imagination are an indicator light that shows us to overcome obstacles and open a new chapter.
After I had a deeper understanding of the problem of air pollution and found the air pollution data of the past ten years, as well as the meteorological data of Johannesburg and its surroundings, I created the Air Quality Resolution Support System with my colleagues from South Africa and China and uploaded it to the cloud.
This software can analyze historical and real-time data to reveal the changing trend of pollution with time and space.
We then used the new machine learning technology to predict future pollution several days in advance.
This means that residents can make better decisions about their daily itinerary and where to settle with their families.
We can predict adverse pollution events in advance, define serious sources of pollution, and enable relevant authorities to issue instructions to adjust their business activities.
By supporting scenario planning, urban planners can also make better decisions on how to expand infrastructure work, such as residential resettlement in industrial areas.
We have established a pilot of the technology, which has been in operation for 120 days, covering the whole of South Africa.
Our expected results were verified, and the predicted data we showed showed showed a close correlation with the data we collected in the field.
Through our management, we introduced the world's leading cutting-edge instruments to predict air quality with unprecedented resolution and accuracy, benefiting the city I drove into on a recent winter morning. At that time, I said to myself, "Something is wrong, I have to find a way to do something."
Therefore, the point is: what if I didn't deeply investigate the problem of air pollution?
What if instead of paying attention to the environmental situation of the country, I hope that some places and others will take care of these things?
What I learned from it is that it is very important to focus on the possibility of success and consider the consequences of inaction when making every effort to advance a cause that we all believe in.
We should not be distracted by opposition and resistance. It should inspire us to go further.
So no matter where you are in the world, the next time you find that your natural curiosity is aroused and it is about what you want, you have some crazy or brave ideas. Even if this is not your field of expertise, ask yourself: Why not try?
Why not go ahead and solve problems? Do your best, in your own way?
You may get unexpected joy.
Thank you.
(Applause)
The largest earthquake in Taiwan occurred in the eastern waters of Taiwan this year.
China News Service, Taipei, July 26 (Reuters) - An earthquake measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale occurred in the eastern waters of Taiwan at 20: 52 on July 26, with a maximum magnitude of 4. The earthquake was felt across Taiwan, making it the largest earthquake in Taiwan this year.
According to the reports of the Central News Agency, China Time Electronic News, ETtoday News Cloud and other Taiwan media, the Taiwan Meteorological Department measured and reported that the epicenter of the earthquake was located 86.5 kilometers southeast of Yilan County Government, that is, the eastern sea area of Taiwan, with a source depth of 53 kilometers.
China Earthquake Network measured the magnitude of the earthquake to be 5.5.
The largest earthquakes in all parts of Taiwan were: 4 in Hualien County, 3 in Yilan, Taidong, Nantou and Yunlin counties, and 1 to 2 in other counties and cities.
The meteorological department of Taiwan pointed out that the earthquake was the largest in Taiwan this year and belonged to the subduction zone type earthquake at the boundary of the plate. The epicenter of the earthquake often occurred in the past and has been relatively active since this year.
In the coming week, it is still not ruled out that there will be aftershocks above magnitude 4.
Many people think that driving is something that only those who can see can do.
Until now, it was considered an impossible task for blind people to drive a car alone and safely.
Hello, my name is Dennis Hong. We have built a car designed for people with visual impairment for the freedom and independence of blind people.
Before I talk about the car for the blind, let me briefly talk about another project I have done called the Urban Challenge of the Advanced Research Projects Agency of the United States Department of Defense.
This is about building a self-driving mechanical vehicle.
If you press the start button and stop touching anything, it can reach its destination completely automatically.
In the 2007 Challenge, our team won $500,000 to win the third place of the competition.
At about that time, the National Association for the Blind, or the Blind Association, challenged the design team about who could design a car that blind people could drive independently and safely.
We think we should give it a try, because we think, well, where is this difficult?
We already have an automatic car.
As long as we let the blind drive inside, it won't be over, will it?
(Laughter) But we were wrong.
What the Blind Association wants is not a car that can carry the blind around, but a car that the blind can make choices and control.
So we have to give up all our original things and start from scratch.
To test this crazy idea, we designed a prototype of a small sand truck to test its feasibility.
In the summer of 2009, we invited many blind young people across the country and gave them a chance to take a ride in this car.
It was definitely a cool experience.
But the problem with this car is that its design can only allow blind people to drive in a very limited environment, like a closed parking lot - even on a path made of red traffic cones.
So with this success, we decided to take an important next step to build a real car that can drive on a real road.
So how does it work?
Well, this is a relatively complex system, but let me explain it to simplify it.
We have three stages.
We have induction stage, calculation stage and non-visual interface.
The driver is obviously invisible, so the system must be able to sense the surrounding environment and collect data for the driver.
At this point, we use the initial measuring element.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration - just like the human ear, the inner ear.
I combined this information with GPS to predict the location of the vehicle.
We also use two cameras to detect the driving path.
We also use three laser rangefinders.
The laser scans the environment to detect obstacles - vehicles passing in front and behind also have any obstacles that break into the road, any obstacles around the vehicle.
All the massive information is then aggregated into the computer, which will do two things.
First of all, one thing is to process information to understand the surrounding environment - which are driving paths and which are obstacles - and transform this information to the driver.
The system is also very intelligent to calculate the safest driving path.
We can also issue instructions on how to operate the vehicle's operating procedures.
But the question is: how can we transmit information and instructions to the blind person quickly and accurately enough to ensure that he can drive?
To this end, we have designed many different non-visual user interface technologies.
The original three-dimensional flat sound system included vibration vests, sound-controlled gears, leg straps, and even shoes that put pressure on the feet.
But today we are talking about three non-visual user interface technologies.
The first interface is called the driving handle.
This is a pair of gloves with vibration elements at the knuckles so that you can transmit instructions on how to drive - direction and amplitude.
Another device is called the velocity shock zone.
This car chair - in fact, it is a massage chair.
We take it apart, and we reorganize the vibration components in different modes. We let them transmit the speed information, as well as instructions on how to use the throttle and brake.
Here, you can see how the computer understands the surrounding environment. Because you can't see the vibration, we actually installed a red light-emitting diode on the driver, so he can see what is happening.
This is the sensing data, which is transmitted from the sensor to the computer.
So these two kinds of equipment, driving handle and speed shock belt, are very effective.
But the problem is that these are instruction hinting devices.
So it's not really freedom, is it?
The computer tells you how to drive - turn left, turn right, speed up, brake.
I call this the co-driver problem.
Therefore, we are avoiding instruction hinting devices and paying more attention to information devices.
A typical example of this non-visual information interface is called an empty graph.
Think of this as a monitor for the blind.
This is a small desktop with many holes in it and compressed air is removed from it, so it can be described as a picture.
So even if you are blind and you put your hand on it, you can sense the behavior route and obstacles.
In fact, you can also change the frequency and possibly the temperature of the air.
This is actually a multi-dimensional user interface.
Here, you can see how the cameras on the left and right and the computer parse and transmit this information to the air map.
In this way, we are showing a simulation program. A blind man is driving with a space map.
This program is very helpful for training blind drivers and quickly testing different theories based on different kinds of non-visual user interfaces.
This is basically how it works.
But this car is a model car, and it will not go on the road unless it is proved to be as safe to drive as today's cars, or safer.
I truly believe it will happen.
But can societies accept this radical idea?
How will we handle the insurance?
How will we issue a driver's license?
There are many different obstacles behind the technological challenge that we need to address before it becomes a reality.
Of course, the main purpose of this project is to design a car driven by blind people.
But potentially more important than this is the enormous value of the by-products of the project.
A sensor that can be used to view darkness, rain and fog.
As well as these new types of interfaces, we can use these technologies to provide safer vehicles for the visual crowd.
Or for the blind, daily living on household devices - educational facilities, office facilities application services.
Imagine the teacher writing notes on the blackboard in class. Blind students can also use these non-visual interfaces to understand and read what the teacher wrote.
This is extremely precious.
What I show you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
